    <h1>Resources</h1>
    <p>Curated guides and tools to help you feel more informed, better equipped, and deeply supported &mdash; wherever you are on your hypermobility journey.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container" style="max-width: 820px;">
    <div class="faq-content" style="line-height: 1.8;">
      <p>Living with a connective tissue disorder like Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes (EDS) or hypermobility spectrum disorder (HSD) &mdash; or caring for someone who is &mdash; can be overwhelming, confusing, and at times, isolating. Within the Bendy Bodies community, we believe that access to accurate, compassionate, and practical information is essential for anyone navigating this complex path. The resources below are a thoughtfully curated hub designed to help you feel more informed, better equipped, and deeply supported &mdash; whether you're newly diagnosed, still searching for answers, or well along your journey.</p>
      <p>These guides include contributions from Dr. Linda Bluestein, alongside insights from medical experts, patient advocates, and individuals with lived experience. Each resource is crafted to demystify hypermobility, support clearer communication with healthcare providers, and empower you to advocate for yourself or others with confidence and clarity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="resource-list">

      <article class="resource-card">
        <h2 class="resource-title"><a href="/resources/red-flags/">Red Flags in Hypermobility Disorders</a></h2>
        <p>Not sure if your symptoms &mdash; or those of a loved one &mdash; are part of a bigger picture? This guide outlines clinical &ldquo;red flags&rdquo; that may suggest an underlying connective tissue disorder such as hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (hEDS) or another hypermobility spectrum disorder (HSD). It's a great starting point if you're wondering, &ldquo;Is this something I should explore further?&rdquo; Perfect for patients and providers alike.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="resource-card">
        <h2 class="resource-title"><a href="/resources/hypermobility-guides/">Symptomatic Joint Hypermobility &amp; Treatment Guides</a></h2>
        <p>Two companion guides in one: a plain-language overview of symptomatic joint hypermobility &mdash; common symptoms, coexisting conditions, and what to look for &mdash; paired with the MENS PPMS framework for treatment and daily living. Whether you're a patient trying to understand your body or a clinician seeking clarity on best practices, these guides bridge the gap between science and lived experience.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="resource-card">
        <h2 class="resource-title"><a href="/faq/diagnostic-criteria/">Diagnostic Criteria for Hypermobile EDS</a></h2>
        <p>Feeling lost in the weeds of clinical jargon? This article breaks down the diagnostic criteria for hEDS and related conditions in plain language. While not a substitute for formal evaluation, it's a valuable tool for recognizing patterns, organizing your health history, and preparing for medical appointments.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="resource-card">
        <h2 class="resource-title"><a href="/resources/low-dose-naltrexone/">Low-Dose Naltrexone Guide for Chronic Pain &amp; EDS</a></h2>
        <p>Curious about low-dose naltrexone and whether it might be helpful in managing your chronic pain or complex condition? This handout explains how Low-Dose Naltrexone (LDN) &mdash; originally developed for addiction treatment &mdash; is used off-label in tiny doses to reduce pain, calm inflammation, and modulate the immune system. It includes conditions where LDN is commonly studied (like EDS, ME/CFS, POTS, and more), plus a breakdown of how it works in the body. A helpful, plain-language guide for patients exploring new treatment options &mdash; and for clinicians seeking an evidence-informed, multimodal approach to care.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="resource-card">
        <h2 class="resource-title"><a href="/resources/explant-questionnaire/">Explant Symptom Review Questionnaire</a></h2>
        <p>Wondering if your symptoms might be linked to your breast implants? This questionnaire helps you explore common signs reported by people considering explant surgery &mdash; from fatigue and brain fog to joint pain and hormone shifts. Designed to guide self-reflection and support informed conversations with your care team, it's a practical, plain-language tool for anyone navigating unexplained health issues and seeking clarity.</p>
      </article>

    </div>

